definition.value: An iron coordination entity, being a complex of mycobactin T with iron(III).
An amino tetrasaccharide consisting of alpha-fucosyl, N-acetyl-beta-galactosaminyl, N-acetyl-beta-glucosaminyl and alpha-galactose residues joined in a linear sequence.
An ammonium ion that is obtained by protonation of the pyrrolidine nitrogen of eletriptan.
A acrylic polymer, composed of poly[2-(methacryloxy)ethyl phosphorylcholine] macromolecules.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide comprising alpha-D-galactose at the reducing end having a N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->3)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl moiety attached at the 3-position.
An acrylic polymer, composed of deuterated poly(methyl methacrylate) macromolecules.
A deuterated poly(methyl methacrylate) polymer, composed of d3-PMMA macromolecules.
A  deuterated poly(methyl methacrylate) polymer, composed of d5-PMMA macromolecules.
A poly(methyl methacrylate) polymer, composed of d8-PMMA macromolecules.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(N,N-dimethylacrylamide) macromolecules.
The zwitterion of L-pipecolic acid formed by proton transfer from the carboxy group to nitrogen; major species at pH 7.3.
The organophosphate oxoanion that is the tetraanion of 7,8-dihydromonapterin 3-triphosphate; the major species at pH 7.3.
A linear amino trisaccharide comprising alpha-D-galactose at the reducing end having a N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl moiety attached at the 3-position.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-glucosamine at the reducing end with an alpha-fucosyl-(1->2)-alpha-fucosyl group attached at the 3-position and an N-acetyl-beta-glucosaminyl residue attached at the 4-position.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetylglucosamine having an N-acetylgalactosaminyl resiude attached at the 4-position via a beta-linkage.
A pterin phosphate that is the 3-triphosphate of 7,8-dihydromonapterin.
An ammonium ion that results from the protonation of both of the nitrogens of buclizine.
A hydrochloride salt that is obtained by reaction of buclizine with 2 equivalents of hydrogen chloride.
A 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 2'-deoxyinosine 5'-monophosphate; major species at pH 7.3.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide consisting of methyl N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide having an alpha-L-fucosyl residue at the 2-position and a beta-D-tyvelosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl group at the 3-position.
An organic disulfide consisting of two D-penicillamines joined by a disulfide bond.
A mixture of flavonoid derivatives that forms the red pigment of plants.
An N-acetyl-D-amino acid where the amino acid is D-penicillamine
A decenoic acid having its double bond in the 3-position.
A polyprenyl phospho oligosaccharide that is a tetrasaccharide consisting of one glucuronic acid, one mannose and two glucose residues linked via a diphospho group to undecaprenol.
The ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the side-chain amino group of carteolol.

A piperidinecarboxylate ester that is the ethyl ester of isonipecotic acid in which the hydrogen alpha- to the carboxyl group is substituted by a phenyl group, and the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 2-(4-aminophenyl)ethyl group.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having five C=C double bonds.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having four C=C double bonds.
A hexenoic acid having its double bond at position 2.
A piperidinium ion that results from the protonation of both of the nitrogen atoms of anileridine.
A hydrochloride salt prepared from anileridine and 2 equivalents of hydrogen chloride.

A piperidinemonocarboxylic acid that is 4-phenylisonipecotic acid in which the hydrogen alpha- to the carboxyl group is substituted by a phenyl group, and the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 2-(4-aminophenyl)ethyl group.
A member of the class of cyclohexanones in which one of the hydrogens at position 2 is substituted by a 2-chlorophenyl group, while the other is substituted by a methylamino group.
An amino disaccharide consisting of 2-(trimethylsilyl)ethyl N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminide having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
An oligosaccharide phosphate that is a pentasaccharide consisting of one glucuronic acid, two mannose and two glucose residues linked via a diphospho group to undecaprenol.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
A methyl glycoside having beta-D-tyvelose as the glycoside component.
An ammonium ion that results from the protonation of the dimethyl-substituted nitrogen of promethazine.
An undecaprenol where the geometry of the double bonds is specified as (2Z,6Z,10Z,14Z,18Z,22Z,26Z,30Z,34E,38E).
An organic sodium salt having benzylpenicilloate as the counterion.
A chloride salt in which the negative charge of the chloride ions is balanced by succinylcholine dications.
A penicilloate anion that is the conjugate base of benzylpenicilloic acid arising from zwitterion formation and deprotonation of the remaining carboxy group.
A dicarboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of a penicilloic acid.
A penicilloic acid where the side-chain N-acyl group is specified as phenylacetyl.
An acrylic polymer, composed of poly(N,N-diethylacrylamide) macromolecules.
A monocarboxylic acid that is D-penicillamine in which the amino group has been replaced by a consisting 2-benzyl-1H-imidazol-1-yl moiety.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of succinylcholine chloride.
